ECLOGA [1432

ECLOGA ΙΙ, GALA T EA.

In the second Eclogue a young fisherman laments the cruelty of his ‘Galatea ', much as in Virgil's second the shepherd Corydon laments the cruelty of the young ‘Alexis '. In virgil, the singer begins at noonday and pours forth his complaint until the setting of

the sun; here, the singer begins at the dead of night and breaks off only at the coming of dawn. There are a few echoes also of Theo- critus and of Nemesianus. Scaliger rated this as the best of Sanna- zaro's eclogues: “ Ecloga vero Galatea longe optima est ''.
